Paul:

I was writing a response to your e-mail with the new font at my office.  
(I pick up e-mails at work and at home.)  I did not get a chance to 
finish the response, and the font is not available here since it is off 
the server now.

The designer of a font has the right to name the font.  You might want 
to use a name that doesn&#39;t include &quot;Shaw&quot; however, since that might lead 
people to expect it to be a Shavian font rather than a QS one.  But that 
is up to you.

I think the font looks great.  I am especially pleased to see &quot;E-at&quot; 
looking right.  I know it may seem petty, but Bartok&#39;s font really 
annoyed me every time I used it because of that discrepancy.  You opened 
up the left side of the letter which should make it easier to read and 
distinguish, especially in smaller fonts.  In John Zuk&#39;s font, the left 
side of the letter was just too close to the right side.  [Jerome let us 
use half-letters, which was good, but there were technical problems with 
the font, which were never corrected.  When writing in it, at times the 
cursor would not appear in the place where it really was so it made it 
very difficult to type.  This may have been a kerning problem, but I&#39;m 
really not sure.  Also, he produced this font pretty quickly, and some 
of the letters are not as well formed as I would like.  After Jerome, 
others designed &quot;junior&quot; fonts.  This was probably partially due to the 
difficulties Zuk encountered and because you don&#39;t have to enable the 
half letters to print correctly.]

I believe Kingsley has some or maybe all of the half letters available.  
That would be nice if you could get that to work properly.  But a 
&quot;junior&quot; font where all the glyphs look correct and print properly would 
be excellent.  I am wondering if your font will leave spaces between 
adjacent letters, or would it appear to have some of the cursive quality 
as in handwritten senior QS?

Trying to remember my other comments...

   1. Your font seems to be missing the &quot;wh&quot; sound, which many of us use
      when we write because we pronounce the words that way. (I say
      seems because of the rectangular boxes, one of which could have
      had the &quot;wh&quot; glyph for all I know.)  It is simply the &quot;w&quot; symbol
      with a hook at the bottom so it should be easy to add to the
      font.  To me &quot;which&quot; and &quot;witch&quot; are not pronounced the same. 
      People who use this sound find it annoying if the font doesn&#39;t
      include it.  By the way, adding &quot;wh&quot; was one of the changes Read
      made in going from the Shaw alphabet to QS.
   2. When I opened the font, in several places there were rectangular
      boxes.  I wasn&#39;t sure if some of these may have been glyphs not
      displaying correctly. (I didn&#39;t have a chance to check to see if
      all the symbols were present.)
   3. The font should have a naming dot.  I don&#39;t remember seeing one.
   4. The font should have angled brackets to use in the place of
      standard parentheses.

Regarding schwa + &quot;r.&quot;  That is the vowel + &quot;r&quot; combination for &quot;bird.&quot; 
The vowel in &quot;bard&quot; should be no. 32 &quot;A-h&quot; + &quot;r.&quot;

I hope this helps.  Thanks again for your work. 

Paige

