&gt; &gt; if anyone else has used Zuk&#39;s renaming of the letters, but you are
&gt; &gt; certainly free to do so. I liked them also. Because of the frequent
&gt; &gt; combining of vowels with a following &quot;r&quot; they can be combined in one
&gt; &gt; connected form, and you will see these in Zuk&#39;s font.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; I will respond to your earlier e-mail later.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Paige
&gt; &gt;
&gt;
&gt; Thanks. Strangely, the character now displays correctly. I don&#39;t know
&gt; what caused the change.
&gt;
&gt; I think this combination (I guess it&#39;s a ligature?) is very important.
&gt; The Earth sound has its own special symbol in the International Phonetic
&gt; Alphabet. I see bird spelled as &quot;bard,&quot; or B-ay, U-tter, R-oe, D-ay
&gt; (or, Bob, Ado, Roar, Deed!), but this confuses me. The no confuses me
&gt; because the sound in &quot;bird&quot; is much more rounded than the sound in
&gt; &quot;U-tter.&quot; To my ear, Bob, Ado, Roar, Deed could spell Bard. I keep
&gt; trying to put the schwa sound and the r together before realizing it is
&gt; the common Earth sound.
&gt;
&gt; Paul
